  "summary": "Franklin Clarke presents Poirot with a letter written by his deceased brother to defend Tola Grey against the accusations of Mrs. Clarke. In the letter, the brother describes Tola as a charming companion who provided comfort during difficult times and whom he considered like a daughter. Franklin expresses indignation that his brother's wife expelled Tola from the house following his death. Poirot assures Franklin that he will use his own judgment regarding Tola.\n\nAs the group prepares for an expedition, Poirot instructs Hastings to protect Mary Deulacour. Poirot explains that because her surname begins with the letter \"D,\" she is a potential target for the killer, ABC, who might attempt a \"fourth strike\" against Poirot by targeting her. After Hastings agrees, Poirot spins a roulette wheel and, seeing it land on red, expresses optimism about turning the tide.\n\nAt the Royal Cinema, a man named Mr. Leadbetter finishes watching a film titled *The Unknowing Swallow*. As the audience exits, a commotion occurs when a person previously thought to be sleeping is discovered to be dead. Blood is visible, and an \"ABC\" note is found under a seat.\n\nMeanwhile, Mr. Castor returns to his room at the Black Swan Hotel. He notices blood on his sleeve and discovers a long, thin knife covered in red residue in his pocket. As he washes the blood from his sleeve in a washbasin, a girl enters the room to deliver hot water. Upon seeing the red water in the basin, Castor claims he cut his hand.",
